objectives:

    This course gives the students a picture of Constitutional Parameters regarding the organization, powers and functions of the various organs of the Government. The emphasis is also on the study of the nature of federal structure and its functioning. A critical analysis of the significant judicial decisions is offered to highlight judicial restraint, judicial activism and judicial balancing. Finally, the students should be able to articulate their independent views over contemporary crucial Constitutional issues.

unit 1:
    Federal system: Organization of State.
    Relationship between the Centre and the State: Legislative, Financial and Administrative, Co-operative Federalism and recommendation of Commission.
    Freedom of Trade and Commerce, Official Language, Local self-government with special emphasis on 73rd and 74th Amendment.
    Constitutional provision of Jammu and Kashmir (Art. 370).
    Special provisions relating to specific states (Articles 371-A to 371-J)

unit 2:
    Executive: Centre and State; President and Governor; powers and functions.
    Parliament and State Legislature: Bicameralism, Composition, powers and function.
    Councils of ministers: collective responsibility, Position of Prime Minister and Chief Minister.

unit 3:
    Speaker: Parliament and State Legislature, Powers and Functions, Privileges Anti-Defection Law.
    Judiciary: Union and States, appointment, powers, jurisdiction and Transfer of judges.

unit 4:
    Subordinate Judiciary, Administrative Tribunals.
    Public Service Commission: services under the center and the state, Constitutional protection to Civil Servants.
    Election Commission: Powers and functions.
    State liability for Torts and Contract.

unit 5:
    Emergency: Types, Effects and effects on Fundamental Rights.
    Constitutional Interpretation
    Amendment: Basic structure theory.
    Schedules.
    Review of working of the Constitution.

books prescribed:
    M. P. Jain - Indian Constitutional Law Vol I& II

reference books:
    H. M. Seervai - Constitutional Law of India
    V. N. Shukla - Constitution of India
    T. K Tope - Constitutional Law
    S. Shiva Rao - Framing of Indian Constitution
    Subash .C. Kashyap - Parliamentary Procedure
    Subash. C. Kashyap - Constitution of India
    D.J. De - the Constitution of India, vol.I and II.
    J.N. Pandey - Constitutional Law of India
    D.D. Basu - Constitutional Law of India


questions:

    Unit 1 - Federal System and Centre-State Relations

        Explain the federal system under the Indian Constitution. Discuss the organization of State and the relationship between the Centre and the State in terms of Legislative, Financial and Administrative powers.

        Critically examine the concept of Co-operative Federalism. Discuss the constitutional provisions relating to Freedom of Trade and Commerce and Official Language with relevant case laws.

        Discuss the constitutional provisions relating to local self-government with special emphasis on 73rd and 74th Amendment. Examine the special provisions relating to Jammu and Kashmir (Art. 370) and specific states (Articles 371-A to 371-J).

    Unit 2 - Executive and Legislature

        Explain the powers and functions of President and Governor under the Indian Constitution. Discuss the composition, powers and functions of Parliament and State Legislature with reference to Bicameralism.

        Critically analyse the concept of collective responsibility of Councils of ministers. Discuss the position and role of Prime Minister and Chief Minister in the constitutional framework.

        Examine the relationship between Executive at Centre and State level. Discuss how the principles of parliamentary democracy influence the functioning of these institutions with relevant case laws.

    Unit 3 - Speaker, Legislature Powers and Judiciary

        Discuss the powers and functions of Speaker in Parliament and State Legislature. Examine the concept of privileges and the Anti-Defection Law with leading case laws.

        Explain the provisions relating to Judiciary under the Indian Constitution. Discuss the appointment, powers, jurisdiction and transfer of judges in Union and States.

        Critically analyse the role of judiciary in protecting fundamental rights and maintaining constitutional balance. Discuss the evolution of judicial review with relevant judicial pronouncements.

    Unit 4 - Subordinate Judiciary and Constitutional Bodies

        Examine the structure and functioning of Subordinate Judiciary and Administrative Tribunals in India. Discuss the constitutional protection available to Civil Servants.

        Discuss the composition, powers and functions of Public Service Commission. Explain the services under the center and the state with relevant constitutional provisions.

        Critically analyse the role of Election Commission in conducting free and fair elections. Examine the state liability for Torts and Contract with leading case laws.

    Unit 5 - Emergency Provisions and Constitutional Amendment

        Explain the types of Emergency under the Indian Constitution. Discuss the effects of Emergency and its impact on Fundamental Rights with relevant case laws.

        Critically examine the concept of Constitutional Interpretation. Discuss the various methods of interpretation adopted by the Indian judiciary.

        Discuss the provisions relating to Constitutional Amendment. Explain the Basic Structure theory and the significance of Schedules. Examine the review of working of the Constitution with relevant judicial pronouncements.
